document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Mathematics

5F6FE6CB4E9742D5AEC910569AD9C41D.description:
Sort
shapes that model
a real-world object
(e.g., a baseball is
a sphere, a can of
soup is a cylinder).

7E4649C9D39847F0B5E1CD517E1A0A37.description:
Compare
the area of real-world
objects.

2B026E9EB1894829AB502A370E509CC2.description:
Compare
the volume of realworld objects.

25B9B91E87AA42AD9982920B80F2D977.description:
Apply geometric
methods to solve design
problems, e.g., designing
an object or structure to
satisfy physical constraints
or minimize cost; working
with typographic grid systems
based on ratios.

3152173B19764C35A494B3ABFAC4C2CC.description:
Given
representations
of density, identify
the one with the
greatest or least
density (e.g., If
3 squares of the
same size have
different numbers
of dots in them,
which one has the
greatest number of
dots?).

557CAB9618E7447FAA4EC3743C72ACF1.description:
Calculate
the density of a given
situation.

D934AD4832D04C838D089EC52C2562EE.description:
Calculate
and compare the
densities of two
datasets in the
same modeling
situation (e.g, Is
the population
density of Ohio
or New York
greater?).

C5E9FE3D7FF74641B039A469851FF944.description:
Apply concepts of
density based on area and
volume in modeling situations,
e.g., persons per square mile,
BTUs per cubic foot.

6038064F445A49388FB5F9723BBB9270.description:
Connect
two-dimensional
shapes with realworld objects.

008AD4BCAC7E462B99386E7B2EF14080.description:
Connect
the shape of realworld objects to twodimensional shapes
(e.g., a window is
rectangular in shape,
a wheel is circular in
shape, and a table
can be of many
different shapes).

44CF09ADB867416F8EBD9A76890FA86D.description:
Connect
the shape
of real-world
objects to twodimensional and
three-dimensional
shapes (e.g., the
trunk of a tree
is cylindrical in
shape; a car is
cube in shape;
the center of
a sunflower is
circular in shape;
a bookshelf is
rectangular prism
in shape).

1348A82DB34A41E583CF38D88E8F254E.description:
Use geometric
shapes, their measures, and
their properties to describe
objects, e.g., modeling a tree
trunk or a human torso as a
cylinder.

319FAAC9B1114FCE929450DF38141926.description: Apply geometric concepts in modeling situations.

6A7D3E848F58434BBA9490FCC94A7A8C.description:
Find the
area of two similar
shapes.

2EBCE170FA2643D2B7CE450E3B2544D8.description:
Find
the volume of
two similar threedimensional
shapes.

1528AD1E22884DF5BBF5467919875D0E.description:
When figures are
similar, understand and apply
the fact that when a figure
is scaled by a factor of k,
the effect on lengths, areas,
and volumes is that they are
multiplied by k, k2, and k3,
respectively.

C9BE63E084AB48B796258872C8BE1B2A.description:
Compare the
volume of threedimensional
shapes.

771A66889BE2467ABDCCB7AC6906484C.description:
Understand how
and when changes to the
measures of a figure (lengths
or angles) result in similar and
non-similar figures.

03D724377EFA463FB5F605C54C370590.description: Understand the relationships between length, area, and volume.

25711A23F0214347BF08F77115A6716A.description:
Identify
cross-sections of
three- dimensional
shapes.

A813D5ACD4A24D509A9B6ABF84E2BC1A.description:
Identify the shapes
of two-dimensional crosssections of three-dimensional
objects, and identify
three-dimensional objects
generated by rotations of twodimensional objects.

CBBDE2E47E7E4462972616BCF8CFB982.description: Visualize relationships between two-dimensional and three-dimensional objects.

57FAE240C46F4D2EB500954534CA0C5C.description:
Sort
three-dimensional
objects (cones,
cylinders, spheres,
pyramids).

131C5C56E8504A8785641183B81FA572.description:
Distinguish between
objects that do and do
not have volume.

B6D0A0466A324E09AA1BC0AC1F875FD8.description:
Compare the
volume of two
objects with the
same base but
different heights
and vice versa
(e.g.,
Which cup can
hold more water:
the shorter or
the taller cup;
given the choice
of different sized
cubes, identify
which would hold
more).

FF040DF5297647E595E61BF20069C13F.description:
Use volume
formulas for cylinders,
pyramids, cones, and spheres
to solve problems.

A0E2847C3F89410CA18CB362CB3B9904.description:
Distinguish between
objects that do and do
not have volume.

F8DCBCB640E34CF0BA8C20D2D7016352.description:
Compare the
volume of
two objects with
the same base but
different heights
and vice versa
(e.g.,
Which cup can
hold more water:
the shorter or
the taller cup;
given the choice
of different sized
cubes, identify
which would hold
more).

DF4F9A1130AF4F55ABD7D855DD927385.description:
Give an informal
argument for the formulas for
the circumference of a circle,
area of a circle, and volume of
a cylinder, pyramid, and cone.
Use dissection arguments,
Cavalieri’s principle, and
informal limit arguments.

D258E2FDEA7D4AA2BCA059FDC067459B.description: Explain volume formulas, and use them to solve problems.

DF8431D693D44CAAA0EFB0730D6C5E5B.description:
Interact with physical objects that represent 2-D shapes in
the real-world, e.g., the lid on a sandwich box, a window,
etc.

topic)

shapes on a
coordinate grid.

Find the
perimeter of shapes
given on a coordinate
grid. (Restrict to
shapes with sides
that are vertical
or horizontal line
segments.)

1E368BCEB01E440AA3127E45ABC9905E.description:
Find the
area and perimeter
of shapes given
on a coordinate
grid. (Restrict to
shapes with sides
that are vertical
or horizontal line
segments.)

of polygons and areas of
triangles and rectangles, e.g.,

line segments.

horizontal line on a
coordinate grid.

a directed line segment

given ratio.

parallel and

grid.

between two
perpendicular

use them to solve geometric

shapes on a

to prove simple geometric
theorems algebraically and to
verify geometric relationships
algebraically, including
properties of special triangles,

circle.

 b. Use trigonometric ratios

parts of a right
triangle.

figure;

transformations to decide if
